msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.sort:87
msgid ""
"For performance, ``sort`` makes a temporary copy if needed to make the data "
"`contiguous <https://numpy.org/doc/stable/glossary.html#term-contiguous>`_ "
"in memory along the sort axis. For even better performance and reduced "
"memory consumption, ensure that the array is already contiguous along the "
"sort axis."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.sort:93
msgid ""
"The sort order for complex numbers is lexicographic. If both the real and "
"imaginary parts are non-nan then the order is determined by the real parts "
"except when they are equal, in which case the order is determined by the "
"imaginary parts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.sort:98
msgid ""
"Previous to numpy 1.4.0 sorting real and complex arrays containing nan "
"values led to undefined behaviour. In numpy versions >= 1.4.0 nan values are "
"sorted to the end. The extended sort order is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.sort:102
msgid "Real: [R, nan]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.sort:103
msgid "Complex: [R + Rj, R + nanj, nan + Rj, nan + nanj]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.sort:105
msgid ""
"where R is a non-nan real value. Complex values with the same nan placements "
"are sorted according to the non-nan part if it exists. Non-nan values are "
"sorted as before."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.sort:109
msgid ""
"NumPy uses `introsort <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Introsort>`_ by default "
"for unstable sorting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.sort:112
msgid ""
"For stable sorting, NumPy automatically chooses the best stable sorting "
"algorithm for the data type being sorted. It is currently mapped to `timsort "
"<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timsort>`_ or `radix sort <https://en."
"wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix_sort>`_ for bools and integer types with a width of "
"16 bits or less."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.sort:118
msgid ""
"For numerical sorts, NaT and NaN always sort to the end of the array for "
"both ascending and descending sort order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.sort:121
msgid ""
"Radix sort is used for stable sorting of bools and narrow integer types (up "
"to 16 bits). For these it performs better than Timsort."
msgstr ""

